                <text type="case">
                                <body xml:id="ch1.sc3.0081">                                                
                                                  <p><name type="person" key="1270"><hi rend="initialcap">S</hi>HEFFLER, <hi rend="initialcap">J</hi>OHN</name>, Private, <name type="organization" key="353">Co. D, 45th
                                                  Pennsylvania Volunteers</name>, aged 44 years,
                                                                  received, at the battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="263">Cold Harbor, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-06-03">June 3d,
                                                  1864</date>, a gunshot flesh wound of the head.  He was on <date type="admit" when="1864-06-03">the same day</date> admitted to the hospital of the 2d division, Ninth Corps, on <date type="transfer" when="1864-06-10">June
                                                  10th</date>, sent to the <name type="hospital" key="172">Emory Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C., on <date type="transfer" when="1865-04-09">April 9th</date>, sent to the <name type="hospital">Cuyler Hospital, Philadelphia</name>, and, on <date type="transfer" when="1865-05-10">May 10th</date>, transferred to the <name type="hospital">Mower Hospital</name>, where he was discharged from the
                                                  service on <date type="servicedischarge" when="1865-06-22">June 22d, 1865</date>, on
                                                  account of gunshot contusion of the cranium.  <name type="person" key="1268">Pension Examining Surgeon
                                                  Edward Smith</name> reports, <date type="pension" when="1865-07-20">July 20th, 1865</date>, that the
                                                  ball injured the frontal and right parietal bones,
                                                  and that several exfoliations of bone had been
                                                  removed; that the patient complained of constant
                                                  headache and dizziness, and the examiner rated his
                                                  disability at "three-fourths, and probably
                                                  permanent."</p>                                                
